            <p>+ΧΡΙΣΤ<am>ϛ</am>
               ΒΩΗΘΙ<gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
               <lb/>ΠΕ<gap reason="illegible" quantity="2" unit="character"/>ΟΣΩΔΡΟΥ<gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
               <lb/>
                    ΙΩΣΕΦΙΩΒΙΣΣΕΡ<gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="edition"
              ana="#b1"
              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="rafi0007.transcription"
              corresp="#rafi0007.diplomatic #rafi0007.translation">
            <p><g type="cross">+</g>
               <expan><abbr>Χριστ<am>ϛ</am></abbr><ex>ὸς</ex></expan> βοήθι <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
               <lb/> <orig>Πε<gap reason="illegible" quantity="2" unit="character"/>οσωδρου</orig> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
               <lb/> Ἰωσέφ <supplied reason="undefined" cert="low">καὶ</supplied> Ἰωβις Σερ<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="rafi0007.translation"
              corresp="#rafi0007.diplomatic #rafi0007.transcription">
            <p>Christ help Pe..osodrus(?)...Joseph and(?) Jobis Ser...</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>A border frames the inscription on this stone, very likely a door lintel. The opening "Χριστὸς βοήθι" is a familiar petitioning formula; the raised S sign indicates an abbreviation. The name Ἰόβις is attested, and may derive from the Semitic איב (Job) or the Septuagint's Ἰωβ rather than Jovius or Jove. Dimensions refer to entire remainder of stone.</p>
         </div>
